      "properties": {
        "text": ""
      },
      "widgets_values": [
        "\u2139\ufe0f Tone Curve (RGB) \u2014 S-09\n\nDefaults: preset=s_curve_mild, channel=rgb_master, strength=1.0.\n\nPRESETS (8 control points each, Catmull-Rom interpolated to a 1024-step LUT):\n- linear        \u2014 identity (no-op, useful as a bypass).\n- s_curve_mild  \u2014 subtle contrast bump (default; safe portrait dose).\n- s_curve_strong \u2014 punchier contrast (editorial / commercial look).\n- lift_shadows  \u2014 opens dark regions (matte / film stock vibe).\n- crush_blacks  \u2014 deepens shadows (dramatic / cinematic).\n- custom        \u2014 paste your own 8-point JSON via the points_json widget.\n\nCHANNEL:\n- rgb_master = apply the curve to R, G and B equally (global contrast / brightness).\n- r / g / b   = apply only to that channel (color balance / per-channel grading; e.g., lift the b channel of shadows for a teal-and-orange look).\n\nSTRENGTH: 0 = identity (bypass), 1 = full curve. Use 0.5\u20130.8 for subtle grading.\n\nCUSTOM POINTS: 8 control points [[x1,y1],...,[x8,y8]] in [0,1]^2. The first MUST be (0,0) and the last MUST be (1,1) (clamped endpoints). x values must be strictly increasing (monotone). Photoshop .acv users: re-sample your curve to exactly 8 points before pasting \u2014 the wrapper raises a clear ValueError otherwise.\n\nPAIR WITH: S-05 Luminosity Masking upstream to gate the tone curve to shadows / midtones / highlights only \u2014 a poor-man's region-aware curve."
      ],
